The Long March
Each nation has its founding myth.
For communist China, it is the Long March – a story that equals the exodus of the Israelites from Egypt led by Moses.
I grew up with that.
The myth is easily told.
The young Communist Party and its three Red Armies were driven out of their strongholds in the south by Chiang Kai-shek's nationalist government at the beginning of the 1930s.
Persecuted and tormented by their enemies, they crossed high mountains, raging rivers, and impassable grazing land, with Mao guiding the march from victory to victory.
After two years and 16,000 kilometers of steadfastness, courage, and hope against incredibly bleak prospects, the Red Armies reached Northwest China.
Only a fifth of the 200,000 soldiers had remained – exhausted, badly battered, but full of defiance.
A decade later, they struck back, defeated Chiang Kai-shek, and founded Mao's New China.
To what extent does China's founding myth stand up to reality?
In 2004, seventy years after the beginning of the Long March, I set out to track down its traces.
It's still a daunting journey through regions that have changed little to this day, inaccessible and incredibly impoverished.
From the 40,000 survivors, perhaps only 500 are still alive today. I managed to track down 40 of them and spoke with them – they were ordinary people who were left behind or made it to the end, but their stories were extremely enlightening.
Huan Zhiji was still a child, barely taller than his rifle, when he joined the Red Army.
He had no choice: they had arrested his father and wouldn't let him go until Huang agreed.
He thought of deserting, but remained, fearing to be caught and shot.
Many deserted.
Six weeks into the march, Mao's First Army had dwindled from 86,000 to 30,000 soldiers.
The blame for this loss is still attributed to the Battle of the Xiang River, the first major battle of the army on the march.
However, only about 15,000 died in the battle, the rest went missing.
Another battle, the one at Dadu River, is at the center of the legend of the Long March. It is said that 22 brave men overwhelmed a nationalist regiment, which was guarding the chains of the Luding Bridge with machine guns, and cleared the way for the marchers.
Mao told Edgar Snow, the author of Red Star over China, that the crossing of the Dadu was the most significant event of the Long March itself, and it is thus celebrated as such today.
However, documents I have examined suggest that the general who led the division over the Dadu initially told party historians a completely different story. "The situation was not as complicated as people later made it out to be," he said. "When you examine historical facts, you should respect the truth.
It's a different matter, as it's presented.
The legend lives on.
There was merely a skirmish over the Dadu.
The local warlord, who hated Chiang Kai-shek, let Mao pass.
As a reward, he later received a cabinet position in the communist government.
The marchers were unaware of their destination.
There were constant discussions about the ultimate destination.
As they converged in northern China in October 1936, this was hailed as the end of the march.
However, the "promised land" was not as it had been promised.
It could hardly feed its own population, let alone the Red Army.
The soldiers had no clothing to protect themselves from the freezing cold.
The women were ordered to turn back and return home because there wasn't enough food.
About a month after the unification of the three Red Armies, the Party decided that the Long March had to continue.
However, it was Chiang Kai-shek's own general who saved her by kidnapping him, who had been appointed by Chiang to destroy the Communists.
As part of the price for his release, Chiang recognized the Communists as legitimate.
The Long March was over.
However, it was not over for the 21,000 men and women of the West Legion.
They belonged to the Fourth Army, led by Zhang Guotao, Mao's arch-rival, and had been tasked with seeking help from Russia over the northwestern border.
However, Mao issued them contradictory orders, so they could neither fight nor retreat.
Surrounded by barren land where survival was difficult, they were decimated by the superior forces of the Muslim warlords.
Only 400 reached the border, while the rest were killed or captured.
It was the Red Army's greatest defeat.
She is still missing in the official historical record.
A Muslim commander took the leading officer Wang Quanyan as his concubine.
This was enough to make her a traitor in the eyes of the Party and to deny all the years she had dedicated to the army for so long.
She and the other survivors of the Fourth Army had to fight for half a century to be recognized as participants in the march.
The participants of the Long March were steadfast, fought, starved, became desperate, and persevered.
The hunger drove the soldiers to take hostages to extort ransom.
The liquidations continued until practically no officers remained to take command in the battles.
When the marchers harbored doubts, they overcame them with the aid of communist propaganda.
They endured their martyrdom with a bravery and self-sacrifice that is unparalleled in the history of China and other nations.
Die Westlegion, die von Zhang Guotao angeführt wurde, wurde auf kargem Land eingeschlossen und von den überlegenen Streitkräften der muslimischen Warlords ausradiert. 
What drove them to do so?
I questioned one of the top generals as to what he knew about communism back then. "I had no idea then, just as I do now," he replied. "I even doubt that Mao himself had any idea what that was." For him, who had survived the extreme poverty and oppression, communism was a beautiful dream that kept him alive, a hope for a just and progressive society.
Nobody knew, or could have known, how much suffering lay ahead, how great the sacrifice would be, and how enormous the difference between the dream and reality would be.
